    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided filing chunks, here is what the document says about the Connectivity segment (Starlink) as a near-term revenue driver, including revenue figures, subscriber growth, V3 satellites, and statements regarding near-term monetization versus long-term investment:\n\n**Explicit Statements on Near-Term Revenue Drivers**\nThe filing explicitly states that the company’s Connectivity and AI segments are expected to be the primary drivers of revenue growth in the near term. Specifically, it notes: *"segments are expected to be the primary driver of revenue growth in the near term. In the next few years, we are focused on increasing the monetization of our existing Connectivity infrastructure and our existing AI user base."* \n\nFurthermore, the filing states that the company expects revenue from consumer subscribers, as well as enterprise and government customers, to be the primary driver of Connectivity segment growth, and that Starlink Mobile will become a significant new contributor.\n\n**Revenue Figures**\nThe Connectivity segment, primarily driven by Starlink, has shown substantial revenue growth:\n*   **Full Year 2025:** Generated revenue of **$11,387 million**, representing a year-over-year increase of **$3,788 million, or 49.8%**. This growth was driven by a $2,377 million increase in consumer subscriber revenue and a $1,411 million increase in enterprise and government revenue.\n*   **Q1 2026:** Generated revenue of **$3,257 million**, an increase of **$782 million** compared to Q1 2025. This was driven by a $656 million increase in consumer revenue and a $126 million increase in enterprise/government revenue.\n*   **Historical Context:** In 2024, Connectivity revenue increased by $3,730 million (96.4%) compared to 2023.\n\n**Subscriber Growth**\nStarlink\'s subscriber base has experienced rapid expansion, though it has been partially offset by declining Average Revenue Per User (ARPU) due to international expansion and lower-priced service plans:\n*   **Total Subscribers:** As of March 31, 2026, Starlink had approximately **10.3 million subscribers** across 164 countries, territories, and markets. This is up approximately **105%** from 5.0 million subscribers a year prior (Q1 2025).\n*   **Growth Metrics:** The filing cites **104.7% growth** in Starlink Subscribers for Q1 2026 and **99.9% growth** for the full year 2025. \n*   **ARPU Decline:** Despite volume growth, Starlink Subscriber ARPU declined by 22.9% in Q1 2026 (down to $66 from $86 in Q1 2025) and declined 11.2% for the full year 2025. \n\n**V3 Satellites**\nThe filing details the upcoming transition to next-generation V3 satellites to massively scale network capacity:\n*   **Deployment Timeline & Capacity:** The company expects to commence deploying V3 satellites—which are designed to offer **one Tbps of downlink capacity per satellite**—using Starship in the **second half of 2026**.\n*   **Launch Efficiency:** A single Starship launch will be capable of deploying up to **60 V3 satellites** to Low-Earth Orbit (LEO). This represents a potential **twenty-fold increase** in Starlink downlink capacity deployed relative to a Falcon 9 launch.\n*   **Current Constellation:** As of March 31, 2026, SpaceX operated over 9,600 Starlink broadband and mobile satellites in LEO (accounting for ~75% of all active maneuverable satellites in orbit), with the majority being second-generation V2 Mini satellites.\n\n**Near-Term Monetization vs. Long-Term Investment**\nThe filing draws a clear line between monetizing current infrastructure and continuing long-term capital investments:\n*   **Near-Term Monetization:** The company states that in the next few years, it is focused on *"increasing the monetization of our existing Connectivity infrastructure"* and existing AI user base. \n*   **Long-Term Investment:** While monetizing existing assets, the company is simultaneously making heavy long-term investments. It notes that the Space segment has relatively lower revenue scale and growth because a significant amount of launch capacity is dedicated to deploying Starlink satellites (capitalized within Connectivity) rather than recognizing customer launch revenue. Additionally, R&D expenses are rising for next-generation product development (such as V3 satellites and Starlink Kits) and the Starship program, which is described as the *"key enabler of our long-term growth strategy by unlocking entirely new categories of missions."*\n*   **AI Investment:** In contrast to the near-term monetization of Connectivity, the newly acquired AI segment will prioritize growth and investment, reflecting its earlier stage of development and the need to build out gigawatt-scale compute infrastructure to support long-term opportunities.',
